-- PRESS DIGEST - Hong Kong - May 13
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Mon May 12, 2014 10:04PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, May 13 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Tuesday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  -- Chinese bitcoin businesses are drafting plans to escape the mainland crackdown on the digital currency as China's biggest bitcoin exchange, Huobi, is considering shifting its operations abroad to protect its customers. (http://link.reuters.com/neg39v) -- China Everbright International <0257.HK>, the waste-to-electricity and waste water treatment company, is in a "rapid development phase" and has not been notified by Beijing of any investigation of its books and operations, according to its chief executive. (http://link.reuters.com/veg39v) -- Slower property investment due to credit tightening, oversupply and sliding prices could pose a serious threat to China's economic growth. Industry observers believe the situation will increase pressure on the central government to relax its housing policy in order to avoid a meltdown in the sector. (http://link.reuters.com/xeg39v)  THE STANDARD -- A leading financier of Hong Kong Morning News is believed to have been detained in the mainland for investigation, throwing into doubt the future of the Chinese-language newspaper due to launch this year. (http://link.reuters.com/zeg39v) -- Chinese Estates <0127.HK> has decided to cancel sales of a project in Macau and pay refunds to buyers amounting to more than HK$440 million ($56.76 million). (http://link.reuters.com/cug39v) -- Zhengzhou, the capital of the central Henan province, became the sixth city in the mainland since April to offer a helping hand to its beleaguered property sector by launching new mortgage guarantee policies. (http://link.reuters.com/fug39v)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  -- A new breed of debt collector, Wonderful World, which will name and share information on Macau gamblers who have not paid their debts on its website, has received over 500 cases  totalling about HK$2 billion ($258.01 million) . It has successfully collected HK$400 million so far.   -- Lingerie materials maker Best Pacific International opens its retail book on Tuesday, aiming to raise up to HK$625 million ($80.63 million) in an initial public offering in Hong Kong.  HONG KONG ECONOMIC TIMES  -- The Hong Kong government is expected to relax its double stamp duty, a key measure imposed last February to cool property prices. Second-home buyers now pay a double stamp duty if they fail to sell their old homes within six months of buying a new one. And this period is seen to be extended giving more time for home buyers to sell their old property.